#The education results show a clear earnings premium associated with higher educational attainment. Households headed by individuals with a bachelor's degree or higher earned substantially more than all other education groups in both years, reinforcing the strong income advantage of college completion. Those with some college also earned more than high school graduates, though the difference was much smaller.

#A notable exception appears among households without a high school diploma. This group was the only education category to experience a decline in real median income from 2023 to 2024, indicating that households with the lowest educational attainment became slightly worse off in inflation-adjusted terms. In contrast, all other education groups saw modest gains, suggesting that income growth in 2024 was concentrated among households with at least a high school education.


edu_summary <- data.frame(
  education = c("No high school diploma", "High school graduate", "Some college", "Bachelor's degree or higher"),
  income_2023 = c(37570, 57250, 75510, 130100),
  income_2024 = c(36900, 58410, 76520, 132700),
  percent_change = c(-1.8, 2.0, 1.3, 2.0)
)

# High school as baseline
hs_2023 <- edu_summary$income_2023[2]
hs_2024 <- edu_summary$income_2024[2]

premium_analysis <- mutate(
  edu_summary,
  premium_2023 = (income_2023 / hs_2023) - 1,
  premium_2024 = (income_2024 / hs_2024) - 1,
  premium_delta = premium_2024 - premium_2023
)

cat("--- Analysis of Earnings Premium Relative to High School Graduates ---\n")
print(select(premium_analysis, education, premium_2023, premium_2024, premium_delta))

# Prepare plot data
plot_data <- pivot_longer(
  premium_analysis,
  cols = c("premium_2023", "premium_2024"),
  names_to = "Year",
  values_to = "Premium"
)

plot_data <- plot_data[plot_data$education != "High school graduate", ]

plot_data$Year <- ifelse(plot_data$Year == "premium_2023", "2023", "2024")

plot_data$education <- factor(
  plot_data$education,
  levels = c(
    "No high school diploma",
    "Some college",
    "Bachelor's degree or higher"
  )
)

ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = education, y = Premium, fill = Year)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent) +
  labs(
    title = "Higher Education Earnings Premium (2023 vs 2024)",
    subtitle = "Relative to High School Graduates",
    x = "Education Level",
    y = "Premium Percentage",
    caption = "Source: U.S. Census Bureau"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
```
