# Findings

@tbl-ageIncome reports the underlying 2023 and 2024 values for each
age group along with the year to year percent change in real
income, and @fig-ageIncomeCurve plots the same values as two
overlaid lines so the year-over-year change at each life stage is
easy to read at a glance.

```{r}
#| label: tbl-ageIncome
#| tbl-cap: "Median Household Income by Age of Householder, 2023-2024"
#| tbl-pos: H
#| html-table-processing: none

# Primary Author: Ethan Tluszcz
#Build age income table

ageIncome |>
  mutate(
    pct_change_label = paste0(
      if_else(condition = (pct_change > 0), true = "+", false = ""),
      format(pct_change, nsmall = 1),
      "%",
      if_else(condition = significant_change, true = "*", false = "")
    )
  ) |>
  select(
    age_group,
    households_2023,
    median_2023,
    households_2024,
    median_2024,
    pct_change_label
  ) |>
  kable(
    digits = 0,
    col.names = c(
      "Age",
      "Households 2023",
      "Median $ 2023",
      "Households 2024",
      "Median $ 2024",
      "Percent Change"
    )
  ) |>
  kable_classic(latex_options = "HOLD_position") |>
  footnote(
    general = paste(
      "Median income reported in 2024 dollars (CPI-U adjusted).",
      "Asterisks indicate that the year-over-year change in real income",
      "was statistically significant at the 90% confidence level.",
      "Source: U.S. Census Bureau, CPS ASEC, Table A-1."
    ),
    general_title = "",
    threeparttable = TRUE
  )
```

```{r}
#| label: fig-ageIncomeCurve
#| fig-cap: "Median Household Income by Age of Householder, 2023 vs 2024"
#| fig-pos: H
#| fig-alt: "Line graph comparing median household income by age group for 2023 and 2024,
#|  showing income increases and decreases."
#| fig-height: 4.5

# Primary Author: Ethan Tluszcz
#Build age income line chart

# Reshape to long format so year can map to color
ageIncomeLong <- ageIncome |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(median_2023, median_2024),
    names_to = "year",
    values_to = "median_income"
  ) |>
  mutate(
    year = if_else(
      condition = (year == "median_2023"),
      true = "2023",
      false = "2024"
    )
  )

# Set the order of age groups for the x-axis
ageOrder <- c(
  "15 to 24 years",
  "25 to 34 years",
  "35 to 44 years",
  "45 to 54 years",
  "55 to 64 years",
  "65 years and older"
)
ageLabels <- c(
  "15 to 24 years"     = "15-24",
  "25 to 34 years"     = "25-34",
  "35 to 44 years"     = "35-44",
  "45 to 54 years"     = "45-54",
  "55 to 64 years"     = "55-64",
  "65 years and older" = "65+"
)
# Build the plot
ggplot(
  data = ageIncomeLong,
  mapping = aes(
    x = age_group,
    y = median_income,
    color = year,
    group = year
  )
) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2.5) +
  geom_text(
    data = ageIncome,
    mapping = aes(
      x = age_group,
      y = if_else(
        condition = (median_2024 > median_2023),
        true = median_2024,
        false = median_2023
      ),
      label = paste0(
        if_else(condition = (pct_change > 0), true = "+", false = ""),
        format(pct_change, nsmall = 1),
        "%",
        if_else(condition = significant_change, true = "*", false = "")
      )
    ),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    vjust = -1.2,
    size = 3.2,
    fontface = "bold"
  ) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = ageOrder, labels = ageLabels) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    labels = scales::label_dollar(),
    limits = c(40000, 130000)
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("2023" = "red", "2024" = "blue")
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Age of Householder",
    y = "Median Household Income (2024 dollars)",
    color = "Year",
    caption = paste(
      "Source: U.S. Census Bureau, CPS ASEC, Table A-1.\n",
      "Labels show real percent change in median income, 2024 less 2023;",
      "* indicates statistically significant change."
    )
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0)
  )
ggsave(
  filename = "images/age_income_chart.png",
  width = 7,
  height = 4.5,
  dpi = 300
)
```

Reading @tbl-ageIncome and @fig-ageIncomeCurve together, the most
striking feature is the inverted-U shape of the income-age curve,
which is consistent across both years of data. Median income roughly
doubles between the youngest and peak-earning groups
(\$60,310 versus \$116,800 in 2024), and then drops by half again
at retirement.

Decade to Decade growth was strongest among the youngest households,
where the 15--24 group gained 7.0% in real terms,from 2023-2024, the largest gain in the data, and statistically significant at the 90% confidence
level — suggesting that the labor-market gains of 2024 were
concentrated among younger workers. The 35--44 and 45--54 groups
also posted significant real-income gains of 2.1% and 2.8%
respectively. Only the 55--64 group lost ground in real terms,
declining 1.5%, though that change was not flagged as statistically
significant by the Census Bureau.

