# Discussion

The age of householder findings reinforce a long-standing pattern in
U.S. labor and income data: earnings rise with experience and seniority
through mid-career.However, the youngest age group experienced both
the largest and most significant relative gain, which is consistent
with reports of strong wage growth at the bottom of the labor market
during this period.I wonder if more recent data would indicate a decline at all age groups due to shifts in the job market, looking into whether or not unemployment is a significant predictor would also bee good too. 

This analysis captures a short-term snapshot rather than a long-term structural trend. A larger data set over the years would be needed to distinguish real changes in income over the years.Big economic events such as The Dot Com Bubble, the 2008 Housing Crisis and the Covid-19 Pandemic all seriously affected jobs as well as income over the past 25 years. 

